<TITLE> Thais split over likely new PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGKOK, Jan 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Fewer than half of Thailand's voters are happy about Samak Sundaravej becoming prime minister this week, according to a poll released on Sunday. Only 44.3 percent of those surveyed want the abrasive Samak to be selected, 38.4 percent did not and the rest were neutral, the poll by Bangkok's Assumption University showed. Parliament meets on Monday to elect a prime minister, almost certainly Samak, following a Dec. 23 election. "The number is not that bad, given the situation is not normal," according to the Assumption survey. Samak's People Power Party (PPP), which almost won a majority in the election, has put together a six-party coalition which many analysts do not expect to last its full term. The university surveyed 3,506 Thais in 27 of 76 provinces. Investors are looking for better economic leadership after a series of botched initiatives by an interim government appointed by the military after ousting Thaksin Shinawatra following months of Bangkok street protests against h
